data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem

In C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` conversions change overload resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)`, the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` is **not representable in a LINQ expression tree**, so it throws at runtime (expression trees can only represent calls to methods on reference types, not span-based extensions).

## The Fix

Force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these ensures the `Enumerable.Contains` overload is selected, which is valid in expression trees.
